South Africa's electricity system is currently under extreme pressure and the reserve margin is likely to remain tight until at least the mid-2020s, Moody's Investors Service said in a research report published on Tuesday. Moody's expects SA will remain dependent on Eskom - which it rates as B2 negative - for the foreseeable future, although its importance could gradually diminish. "Further growth in renewables, embedded generation and new capacity in gas from the mid-2020s, could ease system pressure," Moody's said in a statement. More to follow. 